{
  "$schema": "https://json.schemastore.org/sarif-2.1.0.json",
  "version": "2.1.0",
  "runs": [
    {
      "tool": {
        "driver": {
          "name": "PMD",
          "version": "7.22.0",
          "informationUri": "https://docs.pmd-code.org/latest/",
          "rules": [
            {
              "id": "CommentRequired",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Class comments are required"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "\nDenotes whether javadoc (formal) comments are required (or unwanted) for specific language elements.\n        "
              },
              "helpUri": "https://docs.pmd-code.org/snapshot/pmd_rules_java_documentation.html#commentrequired",
              "help": {
                "text": "\nDenotes whether javadoc (formal) comments are required (or unwanted) for specific language elements.\n        "
              },
              "properties": {
                "ruleset": "Documentation",
                "priority": 3,
                "tags": [
                  "Documentation"
                ]
              },
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "warning"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CommentRequired",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Field comments are required"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "\nDenotes whether javadoc (formal) comments are required (or unwanted) for specific language elements.\n        "
              },
              "helpUri": "https://docs.pmd-code.org/snapshot/pmd_rules_java_documentation.html#commentrequired",
              "help": {
                "text": "\nDenotes whether javadoc (formal) comments are required (or unwanted) for specific language elements.\n        "
              },
              "properties": {
                "ruleset": "Documentation",
                "priority": 3,
                "tags": [
                  "Documentation"
                ]
              },
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "warning"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "LongVariable",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Avoid excessively long variable names like DOCUMENT_BUILDER_FACTORY"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "\nFields, formal arguments, or local variable names that are too long can make the code difficult to follow.\n        "
              },
              "helpUri": "https://docs.pmd-code.org/snapshot/pmd_rules_java_codestyle.html#longvariable",
              "help": {
                "text": "\nFields, formal arguments, or local variable names that are too long can make the code difficult to follow.\n        "
              },
              "properties": {
                "ruleset": "Code Style",
                "priority": 3,
                "tags": [
                  "Code Style"
                ]
              },
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "warning"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "PublicMemberInNonPublicType",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Public member 'OpenDocumentRepresentation' declared in a non-public type"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "\nA non-public type should not declare its own members as public, as their visibility is effectively limited\nto private, package-private, or protected, making the use of the public modifier misleading.\nDeclaring members as public within a non-public type creates confusion and can lead to unintended consequences\nif the type is later made public, as this would expose all its public members.\nHowever, it is acceptable for a non-public type to inherit public members from a superclass, as this is part of\nthe superclass's design.\n\nTo avoid such issues, these members should be declared as protected, package-private, or even private,\nas appropriate. Note that altering the visibility of such members might unintentionally affect the API\nof a public subtype. Specifically, a public subtype of a package-private supertype inherits all public\nmethods of the supertype. Converting these methods to private removes them from the subtype as well, which\ncan inadvertently change the subtype's public API.\n        "
              },
              "helpUri": "https://docs.pmd-code.org/snapshot/pmd_rules_java_design.html#publicmemberinnonpublictype",
              "help": {
                "text": "\nA non-public type should not declare its own members as public, as their visibility is effectively limited\nto private, package-private, or protected, making the use of the public modifier misleading.\nDeclaring members as public within a non-public type creates confusion and can lead to unintended consequences\nif the type is later made public, as this would expose all its public members.\nHowever, it is acceptable for a non-public type to inherit public members from a superclass, as this is part of\nthe superclass's design.\n\nTo avoid such issues, these members should be declared as protected, package-private, or even private,\nas appropriate. Note that altering the visibility of such members might unintentionally affect the API\nof a public subtype. Specifically, a public subtype of a package-private supertype inherits all public\nmethods of the supertype. Converting these methods to private removes them from the subtype as well, which\ncan inadvertently change the subtype's public API.\n        "
              },
              "properties": {
                "ruleset": "Design",
                "priority": 3,
                "tags": [
                  "Design"
                ]
              },
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "warning"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CommentRequired",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Public method and constructor comments are required"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "\nDenotes whether javadoc (formal) comments are required (or unwanted) for specific language elements.\n        "
              },
              "helpUri": "https://docs.pmd-code.org/snapshot/pmd_rules_java_documentation.html#commentrequired",
              "help": {
                "text": "\nDenotes whether javadoc (formal) comments are required (or unwanted) for specific language elements.\n        "
              },
              "properties": {
                "ruleset": "Documentation",
                "priority": 3,
                "tags": [
                  "Documentation"
                ]
              },
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "warning"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "MethodArgumentCouldBeFinal",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Parameter 'database' is not assigned and could be declared final"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "\n            Reports method and constructor parameters that can be made final because they are never reassigned within the body of the method.\n\n            This rule ignores unused parameters so as not to overlap with the rule {% rule java/bestpractices/UnusedFormalParameter %}.\n            It will also ignore the parameters of abstract methods.\n        "
              },
              "helpUri": "https://docs.pmd-code.org/snapshot/pmd_rules_java_codestyle.html#methodargumentcouldbefinal",
              "help": {
                "text": "\n            Reports method and constructor parameters that can be made final because they are never reassigned within the body of the method.\n\n            This rule ignores unused parameters so as not to overlap with the rule {% rule java/bestpractices/UnusedFormalParameter %}.\n            It will also ignore the parameters of abstract methods.\n        "
              },
              "properties": {
                "ruleset": "Code Style",
                "priority": 3,
                "tags": [
                  "Code Style"
                ]
              },
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "warning"
              }
            },
            {
